Introduction

This is a real estate dataset placed on Kaggle which I found recently while researching for the final class project. The dependent variable of interest is obviously house prices. This dataset has up to 80 explanatory variables describing (almost) every aspect of residential homes in Ames, Iowa. The goal of this contest is to predict the sales price of each house in the test set.

Submissions are actually evaluated on RMSE between the logarithm of the predicted value and the logarithm of the observed sales price. The details can be obtained here: https://www.kaggle.com/c/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques#evaluation

Planned Analysis

With so many features in this dataset, it may make some sense to do some feature engineering - removal of highly correlated variables through methods such as Lasso - Elastic Net etc.. Alternatively, I can also experiment with random forest which randomly samples features at each tree growth which should reduce the multicollinearity problem too. I will also be interested to try out gradient boosting methods as I have seen it perform relatively well in Kaggle prediction - related competition.

The next plan is to fix some NA for some numeric variables which had some degree of NAs; I am trying to fix those variables rather than discard them from the analysis completely..The variables of interest are GarageYrBlt and LotFrontage

 sapply(RealEstateTrain[,c("GarageYrBlt","LotFrontage")],function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
## GarageYrBlt LotFrontage 
##          81         259
RealEstateTrain$GarageYrBlt[is.na(RealEstateTrain$GarageYrBlt)]<-0
RealEstateTrain$LotFrontage[is.na(RealEstateTrain$LotFrontage)]<-0

I will be omitting some variable due to the large number of NAs which they possessed; namely Fence, MiscFeature, Alley Quality and PoolQC. These are qualitative variables which I can’t just recode the NAs into 0. Besides these variables, I will also be removing some variables which are problematic because there are just no variation between the categorical levels. Just take a look at Utilities and MiscVal individually.

It appears that multicollnearity is making the model drop some of the highly correlated variables such as TotalBsmtSF. That is a good sign! I will also be recoding some categorical variables which are a little lopsided (inbalanced between categories) such as LotShape, Condiiton1 & Condition2

#Recoding LotShape to either "Regular" shape or "Not Regular" shape
training$RegularShape[training$LotShape!="Reg"]<-"Not Reg"
training$RegularShape[training$LotShape=="Reg"]<-"Reg"

#Conversion to factors
training$RegularShape<-factor(training$RegularShape,levels=c("Reg","Not Reg"))

#Recoding Condition to either "Normal" or "Not Normal"
training$NewCondition1[training$Condition1!="Norm"]<-"Not Norm"
training$NewCondition1[training$Condition1=="Norm"]<-"Norm"
training$NewCondition2[training$Condition2!="Norm"]<-"Not Norm"
training$NewCondition2[training$Condition2=="Norm"]<-"Norm"

#Conversion to factors
training$NewCondition1<-factor(training$NewCondition1,levels=c("Norm","Not Norm"))
training$NewCondition2<-factor(training$NewCondition2,levels=c("Norm","Not Norm"))

#Removing the old variables --> LotShape, Condition 1 & Condition2
training<-training[,c(-6,-11,-12)]

Now, I will rerun the regression model again, using the new recoded variables. New Condition2 is statistically significant, and it shows that having “Not Normal” conditions would have a negative impact on SalesPrice as compared compared to “Normal” conditions.

Feature Engineering

Feature engineering is an important aspect of a data worflow or analysis project. This is even especially so when we have a dataset with a large number of possible predictor variables. All the variables might not be important from a predictive analysis point of view and it is critical that we bring a balance of complexity and benefit in the final model accuracy (RMSE in this place)

There are different variants of Feature Engineering, but they fall broadly into these 3 groups namely:

  • Filter Methods
  • Wrapper Methods
  • Embedded Methods

In this analysis, I wouldn’t have the time to go deeply into all 3 methods. But for the purpose of this analysis, I will be focusing on the stepwise regression (backward selection) which falls under the category of the Wrapper methodology. Basically this algorithm, starts with a full model and then reiterates itself; removing variables at each reiteration and then benchmarking itself against an information criterion measure (AIC..etc). Variables will be removed from the regression model to the point that any further of predictor variables would not improve the AIC further.This final model would then contain the optimal number of predictor variables selected to acheive the best model fit without compromising accuracy.

library(MASS)

#I have to remove all the na values prior to running the stepAIC function
training_naomit<-na.omit(training)

linearmodel_naomit<-lm(SalePrice ~.,data=training_naomit)

#Running the backward selection algorithm

stepAIC(linearmodel_naomit,direction="backward",trace=FALSE)

Now, it is imperative that we do some parameter tuning to “get” the winning settings for the test - set prediction. However, before tuning other parameters such as mtry(number features per tree) and nodesize, we need to first see how large the forest needs to get. Hence, tuning the random forest model to obtain a parsimonous numbers of tree first is a very important step. Here our goal is to find the point where RMSE is minimised across the sequence of tree sizes which we had specified earlier.

bseq=100*c(seq(2,10,2),15,20,30) 


#Creating a list to store the random forest predictions later on
rfList<-vector("list",length(bseq))


#Writing a for loop to run run a random forest model at each sequence and then storing its OOB predictions
for(i in 1:length(bseq)){
  set.seed(1234)
  rfmodel<-randomForest(modelformula,data=rfTrees.imputed,ntree=bseq[i])
  rfList[[i]]<-rfmodel$predicted
}

library(magrittr)

RMSE<-rep(NA,8)

for(i in 1:length(rfList)){
  RMSE[i]<-sqrt(mean((log(rfList[[i]]) - log(rfTrees.imputed$SalePrice))^2,na.rm=TRUE))
}

#Lets get the winning tree choice!

RMSE
## [1] 0.1659687 0.1650383 0.1647968 0.1643171 0.1646503 0.1646591 0.1645691
## [8] 0.1643940
which.min(RMSE)
## [1] 4

From the output above, it is apparent that RMSE is minimised at the tree size of 800 (4th in the sequence of trees specified by me earlier).

After establishing how large our random forest tree is going to be, it is now time to get our hands dirty on tuning the other parameters. Specifically, the 2 main parameters we will be tuning will be mtry and nodesize respectively. mtry refers to the number of features sampled at each split while nodesize sets how small the terminal nodes are allowed to be. We will have to create a tuning grid which contains different combinations of mtry and nodesize and then write a for loop which runs a random forest for each of these tuning parameters’s combination.

ftune<-expand.grid(m=seq(2,20,5),detail=c(1:4,6,8))

RMSEvalues<-rep(NA,24)

#Creating MSE function

RMSE<-function(x,y){
  pred<-x
  realY<-y
  RMSEvalue<-sqrt(mean((pred - realY)^2,na.rm=TRUE))
  return(RMSEvalue)
}

#2D tuning of mtry(features per tree) & nodesize using MSE as the evaluation criteria

for(i in 1:dim(ftune)[1]){
  set.seed(1234)
  tmp<-randomForest(modelformula,data=rfTrees.imputed,ntree=800,mtry=ftune$m[i],nodesize=ftune$detail[i])
  RMSEvalues[i]<-RMSE(log(tmp$predicted),log(rfTrees.imputed$SalePrice))
}


#Combining the ftune grid together with the MSE values
ftune<-cbind(ftune,RMSEvalues)

ftune[which.min(ftune$RMSEvalues),]
##     m detail RMSEvalues
## 19 12      6  0.1638432
#mtry=12,ntree=800,nodesize=6

After initiating the for loop whereby we looped through every combination of mtry and nodesize in the tuning grid, we found the optimum combination of mtry and nodesize which is 12 and 6 respectively. We will then use these settings and refit the random forest to them. But prior to that, lets look at the 2D tuning plot of the mtry and nodesize (detail) parameters.

library(latticeExtra)

levelplot(RMSEvalues~m+detail,data=ftune,panel=panel.levelplot.points,cex=3,pch=22,col.regions=rainbow(31,start=2/3),main="Random Forest Tuning Map (RMSE)") +
layer_(panel.2dsmoother(...,col.regions=rainbow(31,start=2/3,alpha=0.6)))

From the 2D tuning plot generated above, we can see that RMSE generally decreases as m & detail increase. And yes, we do see an optimum spot between 10 - 12 for mtry and 3 - 6 for * nodesize*

set.seed(123)
